did.unittitle: Jewish Theological Seminary collection of Cairo Geniza fragments
did.abstract: Thirty-five thousand fragments from the Cairo Geniza contain invaluable information pertaining to the social, cultural, religious and economic life of Mediterranean Jewry from the ninth through the nineteenth centuries.

scopecontent.p: The Jewish Theological Seminary's Geniza Collection of approximately 35,000 items offers invaluable information pertaining to the social, cultural, religious and economic life of Jews in Egypt and beyond from the ninth through the nineteenth centuries. This collection is part of the Cairo Geniza. Approximately 300,000 manuscript fragments and documents were preserved for centuries in the Geniza ("storeroom") of the Ben Ezra Synagogue, located in the historical old city of Cairo (al- Al-Fusṭāṭ). The texts and documents are written in Hebrew, Judeo-Arabic, and other languages. Rediscovered in the nineteenth century, the Geniza manuscripts provide unique insight into life in North Africa and the eastern Mediterranean since the ninth century. Documents testify to details of both Jewish and non-Jewish life that are unparalleled in any other source from any other historical period. The Jewish Theological Seminary's Geniza Collection is the world's second largest Geniza collection, after the Taylor-Schechter Genizah Collection at the Cambridge University Library. All the Geniza fragments were digitized with grant support from the National Endowment for the Humanities and are available online through The Friedberg Genizah Project

accessrestrict.p: Prior to visiting the Princeton University Library, researchers may find digital images, make preliminary identifications, and obtain other pertinent information at The Friedberg Genizah Project, following the link to the Cairo Genizah. Users must register to use the site, but no fee is required. Requests to use original materials at the Princeton University Library will require specific volume and folio numbers.

userestrict.p: For reference assistance, contact Rabbi Jerry Schwarzbard (jschwarzbard@jtsa.com) or Dr. Jay Rovner (jarovner@jtsa.edu) at the Jewish Theological Seminary Library. For photoduplication requests and permission to publish or broadcast, contact David Kraemer at dakraemer@jtsa.edu.

acqinfo.p: The Geniza Collection is on deposit in the Manuscripts Division, Department of Rare Books and Special Collections. The Geniza Collection will remain at Princeton until fall 2019, when it will be returned to the Rare Book Room of the newly constructed Jewish Theological Seminary Library.
